{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611686"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:15:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:15:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16238"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16238"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0,0.86,0.06,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8929"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67326"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8929"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16238"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52778"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22547"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67326"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe standard approach in the initial management of a patient with a suspected breast cancer is the triple test. This consists of:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatient history and clinical breast examination\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMammography and/or ultrasound imaging\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-excisional biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFine needle aspiration cytology is commonly used in the initial assessment of breast masses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following features is most characteristic of breast carcinoma on fine needle aspiration cytology?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abundant benign ductal cells in flat sheets","Bipolar bare nuclei in the background","Pleomorphic cells with nuclear enlargement","Small cells with scant cytoplasm in cohesive groups","Uniform cell size with regular nuclear membranes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most characteristic feature of breast carcinoma on fine needle aspiration is \u003Cstrong\u003Epleomorphic cells with nuclear enlargement\u003C/strong\u003E. These cells typically show irregular nuclear membranes, prominent nucleoli, and increased nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio. Cell clusters often show loss of cohesion and cellular dissociation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent features more commonly associated with benign conditions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbundant benign ductal cells in flat sheets\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in normal breast tissue and benign proliferative conditions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBipolar bare nuclei in the background\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic feature of fibroadenoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall cells with scant cytoplasm in cohesive groups\u003C/strong\u003E is more typical of normal breast epithelial cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUniform cell size with regular nuclear membranes\u003C/strong\u003E is typical of benign breast lesions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional features of malignancy include nuclear crowding, irregular chromatin distribution, and loss of cellular polarity within cell clusters.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fine needle aspiration cytology of breast carcinoma typically shows clusters of pleomorphic epithelial cells with nuclear enlargement and irregular nuclear membranes.","Cellular dissociation and loss of cohesion are characteristic features of malignant breast cells on cytology.","Nuclear features including prominent nucleoli and increased nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio are key diagnostic features of breast carcinoma on cytology."],"references":["\u0141ukasiewicz S, Czeczelewski M, Forma A, Baj J, Sitarz R, Stanis\u0142awek A. Breast Cancer-Epidemiology, Risk Factors, Classification, Prognostic Markers, and Current Treatment Strategies-An Updated Review. Cancers (Basel). 2021 Aug 25;13(17):4287. doi: 10.3390/cancers13174287. PMID: 34503097; PMCID: PMC8428369.","Kazi M, Suhani, Parshad R, Seenu V, Mathur S, Haresh KP. Fine-Needle Aspiration Cytology (FNAC) in Breast Cancer: A Reappraisal Based on Retrospective Review of 698 Cases. World J Surg. 2017 Jun;41(6):1528-1533. doi: 10.1007/s00268-017-3906-x. PMID: 28160027.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52778"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16238"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52778"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T21:18:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T21:20:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8929"}},"content